@Andrzej
PDA= Personal Digital Assistant
Droid= short for Android. While most people associate the term with Star Wars, it’s actually been around much longer than that. Here, of course, it refers to the Android operating system, not the humanoid robots.

@Andrzej I’m an early adopter tech fan-girl, of a certain age as we say. Some points about blurriness. The Apple Newton (I owned one) had handwriting recognition, on a screen that mimicked a notepad, and the term PDA was coined by Apple for it. You could get a modem (didn’t own it) that connected to the nascent Internet and sent and received email. The BlackBerry (owned one) was primarily a phone but connected to the functionality of a PDA, like contacts and appointments. Frankly I thought it sucked as an Internet device. It was firmly marketed to business users, until soccer moms discovered it. Many things were similar to the older keyboard based PDAs, like hard keys and no touchscreen. The Garmin iQue (owned one) was a GPS/PDA hybrid that merged contacts and appointments with navigation. No phone, though. 

Motorola made an Android phone called the Droid. I had one. It was ok. 

All that said, and I could go on, it wasn’t the greatest clue I’ve ever seen. Once I got the A in ANTE, I suspected it was PDA and thought “meh.”

